{
  "answer": "**Gāndharva marriage** (Sanskrit: *gāndharva-vivāha*), also known as a \"love marriage\" or union by mutual consent, is one of the eight classical forms of marriage (*vivāha*) outlined in Hindu *Smṛti* texts. It involves the voluntary union of a consenting maiden and her lover, without parental involvement, rituals, or bride-price—driven primarily by mutual desire and sexual union as its purpose.[^1] [^2] It is typically listed after the first four \"approved\" forms (Brāhma, Daiva, Ārṣa, Prājāpatya) and before the condemned ones (Āsura, Rākṣasa, Paiśāca).[^1]\n\n### Legality and Status Across Varṇas\n- **Manusmṛti**: Lawful for all varṇas but especially praised for Kṣatriyas (either pure or mixed with Rākṣasa). Sons from Gāndharva marriages are virtuous but inferior to those from the first four forms.[^1]\n- **Yājñavalkya Smṛti**: Defined simply as \"by mutual agreement\" (*paraspara saṃkalpajam*). It ranks among the eight forms, with no special emphasis on varṇa restrictions beyond general rules.[^2]\n\nNo explicit mentions appear in the translations of Nāradasmṛti, Parāśara Smṛti, Aṅgirasa Smṛti, or other fetched Smṛtis (e.g., Bṛhaspati, Yama, Viṣṇu, Kātyāyana). The topic is not exhaustively covered across the full 37-work corpus; Manusmṛti and Yājñavalkya provide the primary descriptions.\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, Chapter 3, [*paragraph*](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/03/translation/#p-beb0f2).\n[^2]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti, Chapter 1, [*paragraph*](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-f1f83f).",
